<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / What if the Bank of England gains more autonomy?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGES would have to be made to the top management structure of the Bank of
England if it gained more autonomy to ensure that its governor did not have
too much power over interest rate changes, a former senior bank official
said yesterday, Peter Norman writes.
Sir George Blunden, the deputy governor of the Bank between 1986 and 1990,
told the Commons Treasury and civil service committee that, if the Bank were
given more autonomy over interest rates, there would be a narrower range of
advice ahead of decisions to change monetary policy.
The governor of a more autonomous Bank would also have more power than his
counterparts in the US or Germany so that an extra check would have to be
introduced to limit the governor's power.
Sir George's testimony against greater independence for the Bank clearly
surprised the committee.
</TEXT>
<XX>
