<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / Banks warned on lending policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH STREET banks should be more open about their methods of deciding
whether to lend to small businesses, Mr Pen Kent, an associate director of
the Bank of England, said yesterday.
Mr Kent, the Bank director in charge of guiding relations between banks and
industry, also said banks could be moving lending managers too frequently
for them to build relationships with small companies.
Mr Kent said banks should question a number of their practices as part of an
effort to improve communication. He said small companies should also make
more effort to provide potential backers with financial information.
He described short-term bank loans and overdraft finance on which many small
companies have relied as often 'entirely inappropriate' and said this
encouraged the wrong sort of relationship between banks and companies.
Mr Kent said banks should question 'whether they could be more open in what
they are looking for when assessing proposals', and whether they could help
companies avoid refusal or withdrawal of credit facilities. He said that
financing options, rather than overdrafts, needed 'to be explored more
systematically'. Banks were becoming more aware that they should offer
finance 'packages' with different sorts of facilities.
Mr Kent's remarks follow criticism by some small business organisations that
banks' methods of deciding whether or not to offer loans and their terms are
not understood by many borrowers.
However, Mr Kent said he believed many banks were correctly starting to
place more emphasis on cashflow and the state of the on-going business in
lending decisions rather than relying on the value of the underlying asset.
He said that the difficulties between banks and small businesses were part
of a wider problem of 'a lack of information and inadequate communication'
between British companies and financial institutions.
It was particularly important that the recovery of small business activity
was not hindered by lack of funds.
</TEXT>
