FT  21 OCT 93 / Hong Kong plea is rejected
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT said yesterday that it would not relent over its refusal to
grant British citizenship to some 7,000 people from non-Chinese ethnic
minorities in Hong Kong in spite of the Lords defeat it suffered on the
issue in July.
Earl Ferrers, a Home Office minister, told peers the government had given
'very careful consideration' to the matter, but had no plans to introduce
fresh legislation.
Lord Bonham-Carter, the Liberal Democrat peer who spearheaded the earlier
defeat, said that he thought the government's response was 'deeply
unsatisfactory'.
