<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / Smith accuses Clarke of delaying rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, yesterday demanded an immediate cut in
interest rates as he delivered a wide-ranging attack on the government's
economic strategy.
In a series of speeches, Mr Smith accused Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
of deliberately delaying a reduction in borrowing costs with the intention
of 'sweetening' tax increases in next month's Budget.
The Labour leader also sought to capitalise on renewed unrest on the
Conservative back benches about the imposition of value added tax on
domestic fuel.
Mr Smith called on Conservative MPs concerned about the tax to join with the
Opposition to overturn the measure during the passage of the Finance Bill
which will follow the Budget. He said the increase in VAT threatened
economic recovery. He added: 'It is imperilling consumer confidence because
people are now realising the tax increases which the Conservatives already
propose will cost the typical family Pounds 8.50 more a week.'
His message was echoed by Liberal Democrats, who said that the proposed
Pounds 1 per week on the state pension next April would be more than offset
by a Pounds 1.60 per week rise in heating bills for elderly people.
Later, Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, said Mr Smith ought
to admit that, if Labour had won last year's general election, 'they too
would have put VAT on heating'.
Speaking at a Manufacturing Matters conference in London, Mr Smith broadened
his attack on the government's economic policies by accusing it of ignoring
the need for an industrial strategy.
He told the conference that Britain had a Pounds 7bn trade deficit in
manufactured goods last year, the 11th consecutive year in which
manufactured imports had exceeded manufactured exports.
The deficit had weakened the economy, added to inflationary pressures and
forced unemployment up even higher, he said.
Mr Smith added: 'This deficit cannot be ignored. It is eating away at
British prosperity and the living standards of ordinary working people
throughout the country.'
Calling for an immediate reduction in interest rates, he said: 'The cut
should not be delayed until it is convenient for the govern-ment's news
management, but intro-duced now when industry and the wider economy so
clearly require.'
Lower borrowing costs should be accompanied by a phased release by local
authorities of the Pounds 5bn they had accumulated in capital receipts, he
said. The money should be used largely to finance new housing programmes.
Mr Smith said that a future Labour government would set up a defence
diversification agency to help defence companies move from production for
the battlefield to production for the high street.
It would also encourage the European Community to set up a 'recovery' fund
for infrastructure, training and environmental projects.
</TEXT>
