<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration yesterday unveiled a new drug control policy that
it said would concentrate government efforts on reducing hard-core drug use,
instead of curbing casual use, writes George Graham in Washington.
Mr Lee Brown, director of the White House's office of national drug control
policy, said hard-core users not only accounted for most of the consumption
of such drugs as cocaine or heroine, but also caused most of the social
disruption and violence linked to drugs. The policy would also aim, Mr Brown
said, more at the treatment of drug use as a medical problem, and not just
on law enforcement.
The new policies have already come under fire from both sides of the debate.
Senator Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican, accused Mr Clinton of a 'tragic
abdication of leadership' and 'slipping inexorably into the old
permissiveness.'
But Mr Kevin Zeese of the Drug Policy Foundation, which advocates drugs
reform, complained the administration might talk about increasing emphasis
on treatment, but was still devoting most money to law enforcement.
