<DATE>931021
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / Heitmann aims to close a door on the past
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Helmut Kohl's controversial conservative candidate for the German
state presidency, Mr Steffen Heitmann, is a passionate believer that
Germany's 'special role' in the post-war world is finished.
'I believe the post-war era has come to an end,' he told the parliamentary
caucus of his Christian Democratic Union on Tuesday night. 'Germany had a
disastrous special role forced upon it after 1945. As far as I am concerned,
that time is past.'
Quite what he means by the phrase is unclear. Mr Heitmann won resounding
applause from his party colleagues in the Bundestag. Yet it arouses deep
foreboding in the world at large.
Chancellor Kohl and a clear majority of his CDU have closed ranks behind Mr
Heitmann, hitherto a rather retiring justice minister in Saxony, to insist
that he is the right man to take over the German presidency from Mr Richard
von Weizsacker, who steps down next year. Representatives of both the CDU
and its Bavarian sister party, the CSU, nominated him last night.
At an extraordinary meeting of the parliamentary group this week, his
supporters booed and whistled at the respected president of the Bundestag,
Mrs Rita Sussmuth, when she questioned his conservative views on the role of
women in German society. It was clear that the widespread criticism of the
chancellor's choice, in the German media, from the opposition Social
Democrats, and from the minority Free Democratic party in the ruling
coalition, has caused the party to dig in for the defence.
Yet what is most remarkable about Mr Heitmann is his very unremarkableness.
As he says himself about his own role in East Germany before the revolution:
'I was never much of a hero.' He is rather quiet, rather grey, and rather
insecure. This was his biggest public appearance so far.
Most of his political views are unexceptionable, well within the mainstream
of good Christian Democratic thinking in Germany. But he lacks the
sophistication of a western politician to present it for public consumption.
Mr Heitmann had a tough childhood growing up in the ruins of Dresden after
the war. His father died in a Russian camp in 1945. His mother died of TB
when he was 12.
He clearly feels very strongly on issues like abortion. He has linked the
debate on liberalising abortion to the rise in youthful violence against
foreigners. The latter, he believes, is largely a reflection of broken
families and unloving parents. Those who would ease the abortion laws in
Germany reflect the same lack of love.
The election for the next state president is not until May. But all the main
political parties are now locked in to the struggle with party political
candidates. Mr Heitmann seems determined to stay the course.
</TEXT>
