FT  21 OCT 93 / Grim forecast for Sweden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SWEDISH economy will shrink by 2.8 per cent this year, its worst
performance since the second world war, according to the government, writes
Christopher Brown-Humes from Stockholm. The forecast is much more
pessimistic than the one it gave in April predicting a 1.7 per cent decline.
However, it expects 1993 to be the low point, with GNP growth of 1.9 per
cent next year and 2.9 per cent in 1995.
No growth in private consumption is likely next year, and public consumption
is forecast to fall 1.3 per cent. Unemployment will rise to 8.4 per cent,
excluding those on training schemes, before falling to 7.9 per cent in 1995.
New measures to help achieve a targeted SKr81bn (Pounds 6.8bn) strengthening
of the budget over five years were also unveiled yesterday. They include
higher individual social security charges and reduced subsidies for
dentistry and medical prescriptions.
