<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 93 / Lloyd's Names vote to admit corporate capital: Market
expects more than Pounds 1bn in equity will be raised by a dozen new members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S NAMES, the individuals whose assets have traditionally supported
underwriting, yesterday voted emphatically in favour of plans to admit
corporate investors, marking a fundamental change in the 300-year-old
insurance market.
The vote came at the end of a relatively peaceful two-hour meeting attended
by about 1,000 Names and will trigger moves by merchant banks and securities
houses to raise more than Pounds 1bn in equity capital for more than a dozen
new corporate Lloyd's members.
The decision came in the face of protests from loss-making Names who have
borne the brunt of the market's recent difficulties.
All seven Lloyd's proposals for the introduction of corporate capital were
endorsed by majorities of at least 20 to one. Only 591 of the more than
31,000 eligible to vote opposed Lloyd's main proposal.
Earlier Names rejected by two to one a proposal put forward by the
loss-makers to adjourn the meeting until January.
Mr David Rowland, chairman, said that the admission of new investors was a
'vital step' in restoring confidence at the market. He said that 'confidence
has been damaged most obviously' between Lloyd's and its Names.
In addition, 'for the first time in our history our client base has been
questioning our relationship, particularly in respect of our ongoing
financial strength'.
He warned that failure to have approved the motion would have led to
continued decline as 'others revel in the business which traditionally has
been ours'.
Mr Peter Middleton, chief executive, said: 'This is the first bad day our
competitors have had for two years'. He said the proposals reflected
commercial realities.
Summing up before the vote, he reminded Names: 'The world does not owe us a
living.' He called the uncertainty over the market's sources an 'Achilles'
heel' and said Lloyd's could not afford to remain 'on the back foot'. It had
to become 'an aggressive commercial organisation whose sole aim was to
maximise profit'.
Calling for the meeting to be adjourned, Mr Christopher Stockwell, chairman
of the Lloyd's Names Associations Working Party, which represents 37 action
groups of loss-making Names, said that Lloyd's should place a limit on the
amount of corporate capital allowed into the market.
He accepted that Lloyd's had begun to manage its affairs more effectively,
but the changes had come too late for Names burned by losses in 1988, 1989
and 1990.
Lloyd's ought to negotiate a settlement to the legal disputes at the market
before introducing rule changes to allow corporate members. However, Mr
Stockwell accepted the unprecedented undertakings given by Mr Rowland and Mr
Middleton that a settlement would be offered to Names by the end of the
year.
'If a settlement is to be achieved it must result in those currently bust
becoming solvent . . . and must mean an end to Lloyd's attempting to sue
Names for what they do not have.
'In spite of all our experiences of broken promises we are going to trust
you again,' said Mr Stockwell. 'Fleeced sheep have only their shepherd to
turn to.'
The working party is also taking issue with proposals for new rules under
examination at Lloyd's since last week which would greatly reduce the voting
power of the smaller Names and those 'trapped' in the market by their
membership of syndicates with 'open years', whose accounts cannot be settled
because of uncertainty about future claims.
Dissident Names accept poll defeat Page 13
</TEXT>
