<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / International Company News: Surge at Southwest Airlines
bucks trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTHWEST Airlines, virtually the only US airline to be thriving in the
industry's gloomy climate, yesterday reported further strong growth with a
63 per cent increase in net income, to Dollars 43.9m for the third quarter.
However, the company appeared to sound a cautionary note for the fourth
quarter's earnings, saying it was too soon to predict how they would compare
with the comparable period's 'truly outstanding' result. The share price
dipped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 34 as investors took profits.
The latest results were achieved through a 61 per cent increase in operating
income, to Dollars 86.8m, which in turn were produced by a 23 per cent rise
in the number of passengers carried. Earnings per share were up from 19
cents to 31 cents.
Southwest Airlines, based in Dallas, Texas, has built up market share by
offering no-frills services at much lower fares than the bigger airlines.
Last month it expanded into the east coast market by opening routes from
Baltimore to Chicago and Cleveland.
Mr Herbert Kelleher, chairman, president and chief executive officer, said
the quarter to September was the eighth consecutive one in which earnings
growth had exceeded 60 per cent.
He said load factors in October had so far been higher than in the
corresponding period last year.
