   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FALLING credit costs and a one-off tax benefit pushed earnings at Chemical
Banking Corporation ahead to Dollars 502m, or Dollars 1.84 a share, in the
third quarter, compared with Dollars 381m in the previous three months.
Chemical also announced the appointment of a new president, Mr Edward
Miller, who will take over when Mr Walter Shipley becomes chairman at the
end of the year.
Mr Miller, 52, was one of three candidates who had been in contention for
the job, which arises because of the retirement of chairman Mr John
McGillicuddy, 62.
Leaving aside the tax benefit, which added Dollars 140m more than had been
anticipated to earnings, and a Dollars 115m pre-tax charge (Dollars 67m
after tax) to reflect costs associated with the merger with Manufacturers
Hanover, Chemical's net earnings for the period would have been Dollars
429m, or Dollars 1.55 a share.
Third-quarter figures at Wells Fargo reflected the benefit of improvements
in credit quality, as net income rose to Dollars 165m, or Dollars 2.74, from
Dollars 24m, or 21 cents, a year ago.
The loan-loss provision, at Dollars 120m, was down from Dollars 140m in the
preceding three months and Dollars 400m in the third quarter of 1992.
