<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / International Company News: Profits at Citicorp rise 18% in
third term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CITICORP, the largest US banking group, yesterday reported an 18 per cent
rise in third-quarter earnings compared with the previous three months. The
result reflects improvements in the credit quality of its loan portfolio.
While pointing to a further improvement in the bank's capital and reserves,
Mr John Reed, chairman, added: 'The best news in our results was in credit
costs, which are declining more rapidly than we had expected, and in the
improvement in the quality of our portfolios.'
During the three months, net income rose to Dollars 528m, or 97 cents a
share, from Dollars 446m, or 82 cents, in the previous three months and
Dollars 116m or 17 cents in the third quarter of 1992.
Commercial credit costs in the third quarter were Dollars 233m, down from
Dollars 297m in the second three months of the year, while credit costs on
consumer lending were Dollars 665m, down from Dollars 708m.
Trading income, which in previous quarters had provided the fastest-growing
source of revenues, amounted to Dollars 478m, down from Dollars 572m in the
previous three months but ahead of the Dollars 451m of the 1992 third
quarter.
Income from foreign exchange trading fell by nearly a third, to Dollars 245m
from Dollars 352m, while securities trading revenues rose marginally to
Dollars 233m.
Through retained earnings and the sale of new preference shares, Citicorp
lifted its key tier one risk-adjusted capital ratio to 6 per cent at the end
of September, from 4.3 a year before. This was still below the 7 per cent to
8 per cent targeted by the bank in the medium term.
BancOne, one of the fastest growing super-regional banks, reported net
income of Dollars 284.9m, or 82 cents a share, in the third quarter, up
slightly from Dollars 281.9m in the previous three months and Dollars
245.7m, or 70 cents, in the third quarter of 1992.
</TEXT>
