<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / International Company News: Corrigan takes full-time post at
Goldman Sachs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Gerald Corrigan, one of the leading figures in international finance
before he stepped down as head of the New York Federal Reserve Bank in
summer, is to take on a full-time position with Goldman Sachs, the
investment bank, next year.
However, Mr Corrigan, 52, will not become a partner of the firm, renowned as
one of the most profitable, and secretive, on Wall Street. Nor will he have
any direct management responsibility.
The bulk of his income will take the form of what he termed a 'plain
vanilla' salary, rather than the profit shares which have made Goldman
partners among the highest-paid in the industry.
The former New York Fed chief, who began his career as an economist there 25
years ago, will take charge of one-off projects at Goldman. He will also
deal with the banks' clients and take responsibility for some transactions.
He and Mr Stephen Friedman, Goldman chairman, denied this would give him
only a peripheral role at the bank. They said the position had been
specially designed to give Mr Corrigan flexibility, rather than tie him down
to one role.
One of Mr Corrigan's first assignments was likely to be a review of all the
risks being incurred by Goldman Sachs in its business, including market and
operational risks, said Mr Friedman. Explaining the need for a full review,
he said: 'We should not just close the stable door after the horse has
bolted.'
Mr Corrigan caused a stir throughout the banking industry at the start of
last year when he questioned whether banks had sufficient control over the
risks they were running in the derivatives markets.
Yesterday, he said the furore stirred up by his speech had a positive
effect. 'There is no question in my mind that it has helped to stimulate a
more aggressive approach to risk management systems and better management
information. I haven't regretted making that speech - even if it made me a
dartboard target in some trading rooms.'
Because of his former role as a bank supervisor, Mr Corrigan said he had
decided not to take a position at a commercial bank.
He will not advise Goldman on its trading activities, or on any bank-related
transactions, until after next summer, when he will have been out of the
Federal Reserve system for a year.
The move into the private sector may mark a significant change for the
former central banker, but it is unlikely to stop him making more
provocative statements. 'Clearly, it's the other side of the street,' he
said. 'But I don't intend to become a wall flower on broad issues of public
interest and concern.'
</TEXT>
