<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / Lloyd's Names see little hope in vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of loss-making Names will today seek to adjourn a crucial meeting
called to admit corporate investors to the Lloyd's of London insurance
market.
However, leaders of the lossmakers, who have been collecting proxy votes
from the 31,607 Names eligible to vote tomorrow, are playing down their
chances of success.
'We have no illusion about the outcome, but we need to put on record the
fact that thousands of people feel passionately about this,' said Mr
Christopher Stockwell, chairman of the Lloyd's Names Associations Working
Party which links 37 groups of lossmakers.
Lossmakers are taking legal action to recover more than Pounds 2bn in
insurance losses.
A vote in favour of corporate capital by Names, the individuals whose assets
support underwriting at the market, will trigger plans by merchant banks and
securities houses to form more than a dozen investment trusts and companies,
which are seeking to raise more than Pounds 1bn in equity capital for
Lloyd's.
The sponsors of five Lloyd's investment trusts have already issued
pathfinder prospectuses, documents used to market their shares among
potential investors.
Mr Stockwell said the working party was not opposed in principle to
admitting corporate investors but felt outstanding legal issues should be
settled first.
'We need to see the terms of the litigation settlement before we can judge
if the terms for corporate capital are fair. Some action groups wish to
press their belief that Lloyd's has got its priorities wrong again.'
Mr Stockwell said he had received 'unprecedented assurances and personal
commitments' to achieving a satisfactory settlement of litigation from both
Mr David Rowland, chairman of Lloyd's, and Mr Peter Middleton, chief
executive.
Professionals at the market say a vote to adjourn the meeting would be
disastrous for the market's image. 'It would be equivalent to putting a big
sign up over the city saying 'Lloyd's ungovernable - do not touch with a
barge pole',' one insider said.
</TEXT>
