<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / Welsh Office tightens control of WDA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WELSH Office is to tighten its monitoring of government-funded agencies
in Wales following scathing criticism of the Welsh Development Agency by the
Commons public accounts committee.
The government move came as the development agency took disciplinary action
against three senior executives. The agency's chief executive resigned on
Monday.
Speaking in the Commons, Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, said that
government-funded agencies in Wales had been 'reminded of the need for the
highest standards of probity and fairness in the conduct of public business
and of the requirement to comply with rules and guidance'. His intention was
'to achieve a more strategic and effective style of monitoring'.
Mr Redwood was giving his response to the Commons Public Accounts
Committee's critical report on the WDA which was published in July.
The committee attacked the Welsh Office and the WDA's senior management for
'a catalogue of serious and inexcusable breaches of expected standards of
control and accountability'.
The MPs criticised such matters as the recruitment of a convicted fraudster
as a marketing director and an unauthorised redundancy scheme.
Mr Redwood, who became Welsh secretary in May, said it was clear from an
independent inquiry into the committee's findings that his predecessors,
Lord Walker and Mr David Hunt, were not to blame and 'the primary
responsibility lay at executive level in the WDA'.
Mr Ron Davies, Labour's shadow Welsh secretary, said Mr Redwood had been
'almost contrite' in acknowledging the extent to which the WDA 'ran out of
control'.
Mr David Rowe-Beddoe, chairman of the WDA, said the agency would implement
the recommendations of the inquiry. In addition, he would carry out a review
of the agency's organisation.
Mr Rowe-Beddoe disclosed that Mr Michael Henry, an executive director, had
been dismissed; Mr Ian Rooks, marketing director, had been demoted; and Mr
Alun Daniel, director of rural initiatives, had been reprimanded.
</TEXT>
