FT  20 OCT 93 / Names aim to headoff Lloyd's plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LOSSMAKING Names
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the individuals whose assets support underwriting - will today seek to
adjourn a crucial meeting called to admit corporate investors to the Lloyd's
of London insurance market.
However, leaders of the loss makers, who have been collecting proxy votes
from the 31,607 Names eligible to vote tomorrow, concede they may not
succeed in their effort.
'We have no illusion about the outcome but we need to put on record the fact
that thousands of people feel passionately about this,' said Mr Christopher
Stockwell, chairman of the Lloyd's Names Associations Working Party (LNAWP),
which links 37 action groups of lossmakers. Lossmakers are taking legal
action to recover more than Pounds 2bn in insurance losses.
A vote in favour of corporate capital by Names will trigger plans by
merchant banks and securities houses to form more than a dozen investment
trusts and companies, which are seeking to raise more than Pounds 1bn in
equity capital for Lloyd's.
The sponsors of five Lloyd's investment trusts have already issued
pathfinder prospectuses, documents used to market their shares among
potential investors.
Mr Stockwell said the LNAWP was not opposed in principle to admitting
corporate investors but felt outstanding legal issues should be settled
first.
'We need to see the terms of the litigation settlement before we can judge
if the terms for corporate capital are fair. Some action groups wish to
press their belief that Lloyd's has got its priorities wrong again.'
Mr Stockwell said he had received 'unprecedented assurances and personal
commitments' to achieving a satisfactory settlement of litigation from both
Mr David Rowland, chairman of Lloyd's, and Mr Peter Middleton, chief
executive.
Professionals at the market say a vote to adjourn the meeting would be
disastrous for the market's image. 'It would be equivalent to putting a big
sign up over the city saying Lloyd's ungovernable - do not touch with a
barge pole,' one insider said.
