<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / Government wins defence votes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government secured comfortable majorities in the Commons last night over
its defence policy but was again warned that excessive spending cuts imposed
by the Treasury would spark a revolt by Tory backbenchers.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, chairman of the Commons defence select committee, and
Mr Patrick Cormack, MP for Staffordshire South, were among prominent Tory
backbenchers who gave notice that they would oppose any attempt to slash the
defence budget by Pounds 1bn.
Mr Jonathan Aitken, defence procurement minister, said he had taken note of
the significant number of Tory backbenchers who had expressed 'very grave
reservations'.
He suggested that there was scope for 'substantial' savings through the
continuing drive to secure improved efficiency and value for money without
reducing the operational efficiency of the front-line services. Mr Aitken
stressed that these were not the kind of cuts 'on which tears or votes
should be shed'.
Sir Nicholas insisted that the Treasury should not be allowed to take
control in deciding Britain's defence commitments. He could not believe that
it would remain properly defended if any more 'substantial cuts' were
imposed.
Mr Cormack said now was not the time to seek to 'balance the books' by
cutting the defence budget by Pounds 1bn. If that happened, he would seek to
persuade as many Tory MPs as possible to join him in voting against it.
Mr Cormack said he had been assured by a backbencher that they would not
take much persuading.
The government won a majority of 55 (322-267) to defeat a Labour attempt to
condemn its failure to address long-term security needs.
Labour leftwingers - ignoring the official party line to abstain - were
defeated by a government majority of 298 (332-34) when they voted against
the defence estimates.
</TEXT>
