<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / US-style warehouse a retailer, say stores
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE leading supermarket chains launched a High Court action yesterday to
block planning permission given for an American 'warehouse club' to trade in
Thurrock, Essex.
Mr David Pannick QC, for the supermarkets, challenged Thurrock Borough
Council's decision to treat Costco as a wholesaler rather than a retailer.
Evidence from Costco's US operations showed that 35 per cent of sales were
made to the public and the planning application made no mention of the
conditions for club membership.
Mr Richard Humphreys, for the council, said planning permission had been
granted on condition that the proportion of sales to the public would not
rise above 35 per cent and so not damage other local traders. Costco also
marketed a far more limited range of products than supermarkets. Items would
be sold in bulk, appealing more to business buyers than the public.
The case is being watched closely by sectors of the retail trade concerned
about the impact the arrival of warehouse clubs could have on traditional UK
shopping outlets.
Thurrock has given planning permission for the US company Costco to build a
12,880 sq m warehouse at the Lakeside trading estate. The warehouse will
sell a range of products in bulk and at a heavy discount to members of the
club - usually businesses - and to the public.
J. Sainsbury, Safeway and Tesco have objected to the proposed development,
claiming the council acted unlawfully by treating it as a wholesaler rather
than a retailer, and so did not use planning criteria applied to proposed
supermarket developments.
Planning criteria on Thurrock's land use, which place a higher priority on
commercial and industrial projects than retail operations, were not
considered, they say.
The hearing is expected to end today.
</TEXT>
