<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / Dockyard labour terms in danger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FULL-SCALE privatisation of Devonport and Rosyth naval dockyards, announced
on Monday by Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, is likely to mean
less generous conditions of employment for the workforce.
Babcock Thorn, the consortium of Babcock and Thorn EMI which operates
Rosyth, said yesterday that it would 'examine' employment conditions,
including pay, pensions and redundancy terms, if it were successful in a
bid.
Unit labour costs at the dockyards are higher than those in comparable
private-sector operations because of terms inherited from the Ministry of
Defence when private-sector managers took over in 1987.
The MoD also covers the cost of redundancies, something that will probably
cease on privatisation.
The government intends to sell the two dockyards to separate companies by
1996 as part of its drive for defence savings.
Both Babcock Thorn and Devonport Management (DML) consider themselves well
placed to bid for their yards, though both want to see the tender documents
first.
VSEL, the submarine builder, GEC, which owns the Yarrow warship yard,
British Aerospace and Rolls-Royce all registered an interest in bidding for
the yards when the MoD asked for expressions of interest last year.
As well as being concerned about employment terms, unions at the yards fear
privatisation will lead to further redundancies.
Despite winning the contract to refit Trident submarines in July, DML
announced this month a further 500 redundancies which will reduce the
workforce to 4,400, while Rosyth has cut its workforce from 4,100 to under
3,700 since the start of the year.
Babcock Thorn said yesterday that job cuts after privatisation depended on
how successful Rosyth was at winning warship and outside commercial work.
Mr Peter Whitehouse, business development manager of DML, said the company
regarded itself in 'a very strong position as sitting tenants' to bid
successfully for the yard.
</TEXT>
