<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / Training sale to 'fraudster' attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR MPs yesterday stepped up their attack on the government for failing
to prevent 13 privatised skill centres being acquired by a company whose
chief executive, Mr Patrick Doyle, was a 'convicted fraudster'.
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow employment secretary, said in the Commons that Mr
Doyle, chief executive of AST Training, had been imprisoned for 'forgery and
fraud'.
Mr Rhodri Morgan, a Labour frontbencher, is among the signatories of a
motion which levels a charge of 'collusion' against Arthur Andersen,
receivers of Astra Training Services, the privatised skillcentre network of
the Department of Employment. It claims that 'alternative purchasers were
unable to get information from Arthur Andersen'.
Miss Ann Widdecombe, employment minister, said the government had no power
to tell the receiver 'to whom he should sell the assets of a private
company'. She said the government had been assured by the training and
employment councils that they could supply all the training that used to be
provided by the closed Astra outlets.
</TEXT>
