<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / New stock market listings boosted by venture capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY HALF of the companies that obtained a London stock market listing in
the year to the end of June were financed at some stage in their development
by venture capital.
Of the 75 companies that gained a listing in the period, 36 - or 48 per cent
 -had received venture-capital finance, the British Venture Capital
Association said yesterday.
Half of the venture-backed companies which floated had been formed by
management buy-outs.
The remainder had been supported by the venture-capital industry in the
start-up, early stage or development phases.
Most of the companies that went to market were still quite small. Nine had
an initial capitalisation of less than Pounds 20m while 11 were in the range
of Pounds 20m to Pounds 50m.
Among the largest recent listings that were venture backed were Anglian
Group, a double-glazing manufacturer capitalised at its listing at Pounds
183m, and MFI, a furniture retailer and manufacturer, capitalised at Pounds
668m. Both were originally buy-outs.
Listings have returned to favour after a long period during which most
venture-capital backed companies were sold to another company.
Buyers seeking to expand could usually offer more than a company could raise
by flotation.
</TEXT>
