<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / Watchdog lists executive dodges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Audit Office report highlights some disqualification cases:
A case pending: a retail company went into liquidation in 1992 with debts of
Pounds 400,000. The directors had been previously responsible for two
companies which failed in similar circumstances. Conduct included
misapplication of goods and company funds, excessive director remuneration
and expenses, retention of customer deposits while knowingly insolvent, and
failure to keep adequate accounts books.
A case leading to disqualification of two directors for 10 years: a
manufacturing company entered voluntary liquidation in 1989 with debts of
more than Pounds 500,000. The directors advanced monies to a connected
company without due consideration; carried out transactions to the detriment
of specific creditors; maintained insufficient accounting records; and
traded without reasonable prospect of payment of creditors.
Insolvency practitioners also gave examples of the type of actions taken by
unfit directors.
A typical director of a company engaging in unfit conduct may have
deliberately paid off a bank overdraft in the months before the company
failed because the overdraft was secured against his or her own property.
Directors often reduce outstanding loans they have made to their company
before collapse, using their knowledge of the state of the finances unfairly
to put them ahead of other creditors to the company.
They may well be consistently late in paying tax to the Inland Revenue,
value added tax to Customs and Excise, and in sending annual returns to
Companies House.
Mr John Alexander, corporate insolvency partner with Pannell Kerr Forster in
London, said he often came across cases of directors who had used company
funds to pay for house extensions at the same time as rebuilding work at
their factory.
They may have holiday homes overseas, pay their spouses as though they were
company employees and give their children company cars. There may also be
corporate hospitality boxes at football or rugby clubs.
</TEXT>
