FT  20 OCT 93 / Minister pressed on industry aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMANDS for government help for manufacturing were stepped up yesterday by
the Confederation of British Industry and the Engineering Employers'
Federation.
Both organisations called for new policies to encourage investment in
industry, claiming such moves were vital if companies were to raise finance
for expansion.
The CBI said at a manufacturing seminar in Birmingham attended by Mr Tim
Sainsbury, industry minister, that the government should replace the
Business Expansion Scheme with a new system to raise 'seedbed finance'.
Mr Mark Radcliffe, CBI adviser on industry, said: 'The government is not
doing enough in areas where it has unique responsibility. We want to see
more help for new small and medium-size companies and enhanced credits for
exporters.'
His call was backed by Mr Neil Johnson, director-general of the Engineering
Employers' Federation.
He said the government must restructure tax allowances for investors.
The minister, however, said industry did not want to see government
intervention beyond the pursuit of a low inflation strategy for growth.
London's economy was yesterday given a qualified seal of approval by the
London Chamber of Commerce, which reported a slow improvement in business
but continued job losses, Peter Norman writes.
In the chamber's third quarter survey of member companies, both
manufacturing and service sectors reported improved domestic activity with
more businesses expecting profits to rise in the months ahead than at any
time in the past 3 1/2 years. Exports weakened, however, particularly among
manufacturing companies.
