<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / PM refuses to axe charity tax relief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS in a Home Office-sponsored report that charitable tax relief
should be abolished were firmly rejected by Mr John Major last night.
'It is the privilege of everyone to submit reports to government
departments, but it is the right of government ministers to reject them,' he
said. 'And this prime minister does just that. I want to make it clear that
tax relief for charitable giving is here to stay.'
Abolition of tax relief was among a range of controversial recommendations
in a report by three former advisers to the Home Office's voluntary services
unit.
Mr Major told Business in the Community's Per Cent Club - a group of leading
companies committed to community involvement - that the government had
increased incentives for individual and corporate charitable donations
through the inheritance, income and corporation tax systems. 'I stand
four-square behind the tax concessions we have made to the voluntary
sector,' he said.
Voluntary-sector leaders will be relieved that Mr Major has stamped on the
suggestion of withdrawing tax concessions.
Other aspects of the report - notably a suggestion that charities providing
government-funded welfare services should surrender their campaigning role -
has stimulated considerable debate.
Mr Major announced other initiatives to promote the voluntary sector in his
speech. These included plans for a national network of volunteers.
A new award scheme will encourage people to offer themselves for voluntary
work. Local organisations will be able to bid for grants for projects that
increase the scale and impact of voluntary effort. The first awards will be
made next year.
The government, said Mr Major, was working with the Prince's Trust charity
to encourage more young volunteers, and the number of awards for voluntary
service would double to more than 300 in future honours lists.
A deregulation task force studying burdens on the voluntary sector is due to
report by Christmas and, the prime minister said, has already identified 50
potential areas for reform. 'When you have to obtain more than 10 different
licences or permits just to run the village hall, when you spend more time
fending off environmental health officers, social workers, fire officers
than giving the service you want to give, then no wonder some people think
it's not worth it. They give their time for free, they don't expect it to be
wasted by bureaucracy.'
</TEXT>
