<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / FO 'ignored' fears on Jordan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN Office officials deliberately ignored intelligence experts who were
worried that Jordan might be used for diverting weapons of mass destruction
to Iraq, the Scott inquiry heard yesterday.
As a result, Jordan's name was obliterated from a list of suspect countries
published in parliament in December 1991.
Mr Simon Fuller, who headed the Foreign Office's Near East and North Africa
department between 1990 and 1993, described a series of intelligence reports
on sanctions-busting in Jordan as irrelevant to the country's inclusion on
the list.
One report said chemicals which could be used in explosives were going to
Iraq through Jordan in September 1991. Another report said that officials of
Technology and Development Group, the former London-based nerve centre for
Iraqi procurement, were attempting to re-establish their operation in
Jordan.
Mr Fuller said he had supported the removal of Jordan from the list in spite
of the opposition of defence intelligence experts at a Cabinet Office
meeting where the matter was discussed. Three intelligence officials had
left the meeting believing Jordan would be listed.
In a heated exchange with Lord Justice Scott, Mr Fuller said the government
would have been accusing Jordan of a 'heinous crime' had it included the
country on its list. This was because the listing would suggest there had
been irrefutable evidence that Jordan was diverting exports to supply Iraq's
chemical weapons programme where no such evidence existed.
Lord Justice Scott described his suggestion as 'fanciful'. Mr Fuller told
the inquiry that he knew of only one instance since 1985 of a British
military export to Jordan diverted on to Iraq.
He said that the matter had been raised with King Hussein of Jordan, who
promised that diversions would not happen again.
Mr Fuller added that the Joint Intelligence Committee, the main Whitehall
body responsible for security, had not turned up any evidence of military
deliveries from Jordan to Iraq since the imposition of UN sanctions at the
time of the invasion of Kuwait.
He said this had been the case up to the end of 1991 and still remains to
his knowledge.
</TEXT>
<XX>
