<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / CIS states could help Georgia to protect supply lifeline
from rebel attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some CIS member states could act together to help Georgia protect a supply
lifeline from rebel attack but Moscow would not intervene on its own, two
Russian cabinet ministers said yesterday, Reuter reports.
Mr Andrei Kozyrev, foreign minister, responding to a late-night appeal for
military assistance by Georgia's leader, Mr Eduard Shevardnadze, told
Interfax news agency that Russia would not send in troops by itself. The
Russian defence minister, Mr Pavel Grachev, speaking in Finland, echoed his
words. 'Nobody intends to interfere in Georgia's internal affairs or civil
war,' he said, 'but it is necessary to protect the Tbilisi-Poti road.
Probably tough measures will be needed.'
Rebels backing ex-president Zviad Gamsakhurdia have made strong gains in
western Georgia in recent days, not only threatening supplies to the
capital, Tbilisi, and to Russian units based in the country, but also to
Armenia and Azerbaijan, who fear the fighting will throttle their supply
routes.
</TEXT>
