<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 93 / EC plans 5 per cent jobless target: Employment package urges
wage restraint and lower labour costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission is calling for wage restraint, a reduction in
companies' welfare obligations, and tax incentives for training, as part of
a radical plan to reduce unemployment in the European Community from the
current 10.4 per cent to 5 per cent by the year 2000.
The plan, spelt out yesterday by Mr Padraig Flynn, the EC social affairs
commissioner, aims to combine 'solidarity and competitiveness' and will form
a key element of Mr Jacques Delors' White Paper on Growth, Competitiveness
and Employment, due to be published next month. Although Mr Flynn rejected
wholesale labour market deregulation, he went further than before in
spelling out the changes required to traditional forms of labour protection
and the sacrifices needed from the securely employed.
'I believe we should encourage increases in hourly wages below the rate of
productivity growth, not in order to reduce wages, but in order to increase
the number of jobs that can be made available,' said Mr Flynn, addressing a
three-day conference on employment in Europe, organised by the Commission.
He also suggested making employers' non-wage social security costs less
regressive to create more jobs for the less skilled and proposed switching
some of those costs from employers to general taxation.
This attempt to reduce the price of labour will be greeted with suspicion by
Europe's trade unions. However, Mr Flynn has couched the changes in terms
that will appeal to the left: 'Europe needs a new solidarity - between those
with work and those without, and between those who earn their income from
wages and from investments.'
He also called for a progressive reduction in average hours of work per
employee and for 'minimising the financial incentives for longer hours
amongst the better paid'. Mr Flynn said that tinkering with the old system
would no longer suffice and that 're-regulation' was required to take
account of labour market changes, such as the increase in part-time and
temporary work. He proposed, for example, the restructuring of government
income support schemes to be combined with income from work.
Mrs Miet Smets, the Belgian labour minister, said the EC should not be made
a scapegoat for unemployment and claimed that without its efforts the
situation would be worse. She proposed an EC-wide energy tax to promote
employment and an increase in career breaks to create jobs.
</TEXT>
