FT  20 OCT 93 / Belgian social pact tohit benefits system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BELGIUM will today begin the formal stage of talks between government,
employers and unions aimed at reforming the social security system,
improving the competitiveness of Belgian companies and reducing
unemployment.
An outline agreement, submitted to the Belgian government yesterday,
envisages far-reaching changes to the social security system. The brunt of
efforts to reduce expenditure would fall on health and unemployment
benefits.
Without immediate action, the report forecasts that Belgium's social
security deficit could rise to BFr100bn (Pounds 1.9bn) by 1996. The report
also proposes freezing real salary increases between 1994 and 1996, although
it says the country's basic system of wage indexation should be maintained.
